35	Why lower fertility does not have to mean economic decline	why-lower-fertility-does-not-have-to-mean-economic		Business & Economy	Globally, most people say they want two or more children, but many are having only one, or none at all. This disconnect has profound implications for economies, societies, and individual families.	The United Nations has long been a bellwether for global trends, and its economists are sounding the alarm on fertility rates. According to the UN, the number of children people want and the number they're having are diverging in alarming ways. This disconnect has profound implications for economies, societies, and individual families.\n\nIn many countries, the desire for larger families remains strong. A recent survey found that globally, most people say they want two or more children. However, the reality is far from this ideal. Many people are having fewer children than they want, with some opting for just one child or none at all. This trend is not unique to any one region or culture, but rather a global phenomenon.\n\nThe economic implications of declining fertility rates are significant. As the workforce shrinks, the burden on the remaining workers increases, leading to higher labor costs and reduced economic growth. In the United States, for example, the labor force is expected to decline by 10% by 2030. This has major implications for businesses, governments, and individuals.\n\nHowever, not all countries are bracing for economic decline. Some, like Singapore, are actively promoting policies to encourage families to have more children. The city-state offers generous parental leave, childcare subsidies, and other incentives to support families. As a result, Singapore's fertility rate has begun to rise, bucking the global trend.\n\nThe contrast between Singapore's approach and the United States' is striking. While Singapore is actively promoting family-friendly policies, the US is struggling to address the issue. The US fertility rate has been declining for decades, and policymakers are still searching for solutions. As the global economy becomes increasingly interconnected, it's clear that fertility rates will have far-reaching consequences.\n\nThe UN's economists are urging policymakers to take a closer look at the issue. They argue that by understanding the drivers of declining fertility rates, governments can develop targeted policies to support families and promote economic growth. It's a complex challenge, but one that requires immediate attention.\n\nIn the end, the choice to have children is a personal one, but its economic implications are far-reaching. As the world's population grapples with declining fertility rates, it's clear that the stakes are high. The question is, what will policymakers do next?	\N	\N	\N	https://s.france24.com/media/display/805e8312-43a0-11f1-b87c-005056bfb2b6/w:1024/p:16x9/capture-90969876269f1b8f4e1b088-70637069.jpg	As the world's population grapples with declining fertility rates, a stark reality emerges: the number of children people want and the number they're having are diverging in alarming ways.	["Globally, most people say they want two or more children.", "Many people are having fewer children than they want.", "The United Nations is involved.", "This matters now because fertility rates are declining."]	{"heading": "The Story", "body": "The United Nations has long been a bellwether for global trends, and its economists are sounding the alarm on fertility rates. According to the UN, the number of children people want and the number they're having are diverging in alarming ways. This disconnect has profound implications for economies, societies, and individual families.\\n\\nIn many countries, the desire for larger families remains strong. A recent survey found that globally, most people say they want two or more children. However, the reality is far from this ideal. Many people are having fewer children than they want, with some opting for just one child or none at all. This trend is not unique to any one region or culture, but rather a global phenomenon.\\n\\nThe economic implications of declining fertility rates are significant. As the workforce shrinks, the burden on the remaining workers increases, leading to higher labor costs and reduced economic growth. In the United States, for example, the labor force is expected to decline by 10% by 2030. This has major implications for businesses, governments, and individuals.\\n\\nHowever, not all countries are bracing for economic decline. Some, like Singapore, are actively promoting policies to encourage families to have more children. The city-state offers generous parental leave, childcare subsidies, and other incentives to support families. As a result, Singapore's fertility rate has begun to rise, bucking the global trend.\\n\\nThe contrast between Singapore's approach and the United States' is striking. While Singapore is actively promoting family-friendly policies, the US is struggling to address the issue. The US fertility rate has been declining for decades, and policymakers are still searching for solutions. As the global economy becomes increasingly interconnected, it's clear that fertility rates will have far-reaching consequences.\\n\\nThe UN's economists are urging policymakers to take a closer look at the issue. They argue that by understanding the drivers of declining fertility rates, governments can develop targeted policies to support families and promote economic growth. It's a complex challenge, but one that requires immediate attention.\\n\\nIn the end, the choice to have children is a personal one, but its economic implications are far-reaching. As the world's population grapples with declining fertility rates, it's clear that the stakes are high. The question is, what will policymakers do next?"}	\N	\N	[{"label": "United States", "type": "country", "summary": "UN reports: Why lower fertility does not have to mean economic decline", "source_names": 