49	Core inflation rate hit 3.2% in March as first-quarter gr...	core-inflation-rate-hit-3-2-in-march-as-first-quar		Business & Economy	The US economy is facing a perfect storm of escalating prices and stagnant growth, threatening to upend the Federal Reserve's delicate balance. As the Iran war continues to send oil prices soaring, American consumers are shouldering the brunt of the pain, with no clear end in sight.	The numbers are stark: 3.2% core inflation, a full percentage point higher than the Fed's target, and a paltry 2% growth rate for the first quarter. It's a stark reversal from the previous quarter, when growth surged to 4.1%. As the Iran war continues to rage, oil prices have skyrocketed, with March seeing a particularly sharp increase. The ripple effect is being felt across the US economy, with consumers facing escalating prices for everything from gasoline to groceries.\n\nThe Fed is facing a daunting task: how to tame inflation without choking off growth. With the economy already showing signs of slowing, the last thing policymakers want is to create a recession. But with core inflation at 3.2%, the pressure is mounting to act. The question is, what will the Fed do next?\n\nAs the US struggles to find its footing, other countries are watching with interest. In Europe, the eurozone's inflation rate has also been rising, albeit at a slower pace. Meanwhile, in China, the government is taking a more aggressive approach, implementing policies to boost growth and keep inflation in check. The contrast between the US and its global peers is stark, and it's a reminder that the US is not alone in its economic challenges.\n\nThe stakes are high, and the consequences of inaction are clear. If the Fed fails to tame inflation, it could lead to a sharp slowdown in growth, with far-reaching consequences for workers, businesses, and consumers. On the other hand, if policymakers act too aggressively, they risk choking off growth and creating a recession. It's a delicate balancing act, and one that will be closely watched by markets and policymakers around the world.\n\nAs the US economy teeters on the brink, one thing is clear: the next few months will be crucial in determining the country's economic trajectory. Will the Fed find a way to tame inflation without sacrificing growth? Only time will tell.	\N	\N	\N	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559526324-593bc073d938?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1600&q=85	Core inflation soars to 3.2% as first-quarter growth stalls at 2%.	["Core inflation rate hit 3.2% in March.", "First-quarter growth rate was 2%.", "Iran war affected oil prices.", "Oil prices soared in March.", "Consumers faced escalating prices in March."]	{"heading": "The Story", "body": "The numbers are stark: 3.2% core inflation, a full percentage point higher than the Fed's target, and a paltry 2% growth rate for the first quarter. It's a stark reversal from the previous quarter, when growth surged to 4.1%. As the Iran war continues to rage, oil prices have skyrocketed, with March seeing a particularly sharp increase. The ripple effect is being felt across the US economy, with consumers facing escalating prices for everything from gasoline to groceries.\\n\\nThe Fed is facing a daunting task: how to tame inflation without choking off growth. With the economy already showing signs of slowing, the last thing policymakers want is to create a recession. But with core inflation at 3.2%, the pressure is mounting to act. The question is, what will the Fed do next?\\n\\nAs the US struggles to find its footing, other countries are watching with interest. In Europe, the eurozone's inflation rate has also been rising, albeit at a slower pace. Meanwhile, in China, the government is taking a more aggressive approach, implementing policies to boost growth and keep inflation in check. The contrast between the US and its global peers is stark, and it's a reminder that the US is not alone in its economic challenges.\\n\\nThe stakes are high, and the consequences of inaction are clear. If the Fed fails to tame inflation, it could lead to a sharp slowdown in growth, with far-reaching consequences for workers, businesses, and consumers. On the other hand, if policymakers act too aggressively, they risk choking off growth and creating a recession. It's a delicate balancing act, and one that will be closely watched by markets and policymakers around the world.\\n\\nAs the US economy teeters on the brink, one thing is clear: the next few months will be crucial in determining the country's economic trajectory. Will the Fed find a way to tame inflation without sacrificing growth? Only time will tell."}	\N	\N	[{"label": "United States", "type": "country", "summary": "CNBC reports: Core inflation rate hit 3.2% in March as first-quarter growth disappointed at 2%", "source_names": ["CNBC"]}]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	17	2	2	1	2026-05-06 05:31:00.887606	2026-05-06 05:37:05.689545
