109	Why did resident doctors go on strike and how much are th...	why-did-resident-doctors-go-on-strike-and-how-much		Health	For the 15th time, resident doctors in England walked off the job, leaving patients and hospitals to navigate the consequences of the strike. The standoff between doctors and the government has far-reaching implications for the public health system, as well as the careers of those who care for us.	The dispute between resident doctors and the government in England has been ongoing for months, with each side dug in. The doctors, who are in the midst of their training, have been pushing for better pay and working conditions. The government, however, has been resistant to their demands, citing budget constraints. As a result, the doctors have taken to the picket lines, leaving patients to worry about the care they will receive.\n\nFor patients, the strike has been a source of anxiety. Hospitals have been forced to cancel elective procedures, and many have been left without access to the care they need. The impact has been felt across the country, with many patients taking to social media to express their frustration and concern. The strike has also highlighted the precarious nature of the medical profession, where doctors are often overworked and underpaid.\n\nThe dispute has also sparked a wider debate about the state of the National Health Service (NHS) in England. Critics argue that the government's austerity measures have left the NHS underfunded and understaffed, making it difficult for doctors to provide the care that patients need. Supporters of the government, on the other hand, argue that the NHS is a world-class system that is in need of reform, not more funding.\n\nAs the dispute continues, many are left wondering what the future holds for the NHS. Will the government finally cave to the doctors' demands, or will the strike continue to drag on? One thing is certain: the consequences of the strike will be felt for months to come.\n\nThe strike has also highlighted the differences in approach between the NHS in England and other countries. In Scotland, for example, the government has been more willing to listen to the doctors' demands, and has offered them a pay rise. In contrast, the government in England has been more resistant, leading to the current standoff.\n\nThe return to work of the resident doctors is a welcome relief for patients and hospitals, but the underlying issues remain. The dispute is a symptom of a larger problem, one that requires a more nuanced and comprehensive solution. As the NHS continues to grapple with the consequences of the strike, one thing is clear: the future of the medical profession hangs in the balance.	\N	\N	\N	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559757175-5700dde675bc?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1600&q=85	Resident doctors in England have returned to work after a 15th walkout in a long-running dispute.	["Resident doctors in England went on strike.", "They returned to work after the 15th walkout.", "The walkout was part of a long-running dispute.", "Resident doctors in England returned to work."]	{"heading": "The Story", "body": "The dispute between resident doctors and the government in England has been ongoing for months, with each side dug in. The doctors, who are in the midst of their training, have been pushing for better pay and working conditions. The government, however, has been resistant to their demands, citing budget constraints. As a result, the doctors have taken to the picket lines, leaving patients to worry about the care they will receive.\\n\\nFor patients, the strike has been a source of anxiety. Hospitals have been forced to cancel elective procedures, and many have been left without access to the care they need. The impact has been felt across the country, with many patients taking to social media to express their frustration and concern. The strike has also highlighted the precarious nature of the medical profession, where doctors are often overworked and underpaid.\\n\\nThe dispute has also sparked a wider debate about the state of the National Health Service (NHS) in England. Critics argue that the government's austerity measures have left the NHS underfunded and understaffed, making it difficult for doctors to provide the care that patients need. Supporters of the government, on the other hand, argue that the NHS is a world-class system that is in need of reform, not more funding.\\n\\nAs the dispute continues, many are left wondering what the future holds for the NHS. Will the government finally cave to the doctors' demands, or will the strike continue to drag on? One thing is certain: the consequences of the strike will be felt for months to come.\\n\\nThe strike has also highlighted the differences in approach between the NHS in England and other countries. In Scotland, for example, the government has been more willing to listen to the doctors' demands, and has offered them a pay rise. In contrast, the government in England has been more resistant, leading to the current standoff.\\n\\nThe return to work of the resident doctors is a welcome relief for patients and hospitals, but the underlying issues remain. The dispute is a symptom of a larger problem, one that requires a more nuanced and comprehensive solution. As the NHS continues to grapple with the consequences of the strike, one thing is clear: the future of the medical profession hangs in the balance."}	\N	\N	[{"label": "United Kingdom", "type": "country", "summary": "BBC reports: Why did resident doctors go on strike and how much are they paid?", "source_names": ["BBC"]}, {"label": "United States", "type": "country", "summary": "Scientific American reports: Why the FDA rejected a \\u2018breakthrough\\u2019 melanoma drug", "source_names": ["Scientific American"]}]	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	19	2	2	2	2026-05-06 05:31:01.340604	2026-05-06 05:44:56.140107
