1	Trump Halts US Operation in Strait of Hormuz	trump-halts-us-operation-in-strait-of-hormuz		World & Conflict	Donald Trump has ordered the military to halt its effort to reopen the Strait of Hormuz, a critical waterway that connects the Persian Gulf to the Gulf of Oman. The move has significant implications for global trade and the risk of conflict in the region.	The Strait of Hormuz, a narrow waterway that separates Iran from Oman, has been a focal point of tensions between the US and Iran. The US military had been guiding ships through the strait to ensure safe passage, but now that effort has been paused. The move is seen as a bid by the US to make a deal with Iran, but it also increases the risk of conflict in the region.\n\nThe US military's operation in the Strait of Hormuz was a response to a series of incidents involving Iranian vessels and oil tankers. Iran has long been wary of US military presence in the region, and the pause in the operation may be seen as a concession to Iranian demands. However, the move also raises questions about the US commitment to protecting its allies and interests in the region.\n\nThe pause in the operation has significant implications for global trade. The Strait of Hormuz is a critical waterway that connects the Persian Gulf to the Gulf of Oman, and any disruption to shipping in the region can have far-reaching consequences. The US, along with its allies, has a significant stake in maintaining the flow of oil and other goods through the strait.\n\nThe situation in the Strait of Hormuz is fragile, and the pause in the US military operation has raised concerns about the risk of sliding back into all-out war. The US and Iran have been engaged in a cycle of escalation and de-escalation, with both sides vying for leverage in the region. The pause in the operation may be seen as a attempt to break this cycle, but it also increases the risk of miscalculation and conflict.\n\nThe US military's decision to pause its operation in the S