102	Cruise Ship Hantavirus Outbreak Confirmed by WHO	cruise-ship-hantavirus-outbreak-confirmed-by-who		Health	The World Health Organization (WHO) has confirmed two cases of hantavirus on a cruise ship, where the virus has spread between passengers, resulting in three deaths. As the world grapples with the implications of human-to-human transmission, the incident highlights the vulnerability of global travel to disease outbreaks.	The World Health Organization (WHO) has confirmed two cases of hantavirus on a cruise ship, where the virus has spread between passengers, resulting in three deaths. This rare occurrence has sparked global health concerns, as hantavirus is typically transmitted through contact with infected rodents or their droppings. The WHO's confirmation of human-to-human transmission has raised questions about the virus's potential for spread and the effectiveness of current public health measures.\n\nThe cruise ship, which has been identified as the epicenter of the outbreak, has been at the center of international attention. The WHO has emphasized the need for vigilance in monitoring and responding to disease outbreaks, particularly in the context of global travel. As the world grapples with the implications of human-to-human transmission, the incident highlights the vulnerability of global travel to disease outbreaks.\n\nIn the United Kingdom, the BBC has focused on the rare nature of hantavirus transmission between humans, with a headline that reads: **"Hantavirus may have spread between passengers on cruise ship, WHO says"**. The article notes that hantavirus is typically a rural disease, transmitted through contact with infected rodents or their droppings.\n\nIn the United States, Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance, has highlighted the need for comprehensive public health measures to prevent disease outbreaks on cruise ships. The article notes that cruise ships are often "petri dishes" for disease transmission, due to the close quarters and high turnover o